- Yingkou Kyushu Refractories Co . Ltd ,
- Yingkou Guangyang Refractories Co . Ltd ,
- Dashiqiao Sanqiang Refractory Materials Co . Ltd ,
- Yingkou Qinghua Refractories Co .
3 . Normal value
3.1 Determination of the normal value for all executing manufacturers without MWB
a ) Comparative country
35 . Pursuant to Article 2 ( 7 ) of the Basic Regulation , in the case of imports from countries without a market economy and , if companies cannot be granted an MWB , from countries referred to in Article 2 ( 7 ) ( b ) of the Basic Regulation , the normal value must be determined on the basis of the price or the calculated value in a comparative country .
( 36 ) In the announcement of the opening of proceedings , the Commission had proposed Turkey as an appropriate comparative country for determining the normal value for the People &amp; apos ; s Republic of China and invited the interested parties to comment on this .
( 37 ) Some interested parties objected to this proposal .
the main arguments they made against Turkey were :
- lack of competition on the Turkish domestic market ( there are only three manufacturers in Turkey ) ;
- production in Turkey corresponds to 1.3 % of Chinese production ;
- the cost structure of Chinese manufacturers differs from that of Turkish manufacturers in terms of labour and raw material costs ;
- the economic and cultural relations of the People &apos;s Republic of China and Turkey with the EU differ because Turkey is closer to Europe , has benefited from a customs union with the EU since 1995 and aligns its legislation with the EU in the light of the negotiations on Turkey &apos;s accession to the EU ;
- the Turkish currency lost much of its value ; some Turkish manufacturers are associated with applicants ;
- the quality of Turkish goods is too low .
( 38 ) The interested parties proposed India or Russia as suitable comparative countries .
( 39 ) The Commission sought to cooperate from other potential comparative countries such as Russia , India , Japan , South Korea , the United States of America , Serbia and Montenegro and South Africa .
Of the 38 companies around the world with which she contacted , only two agreed to work in the US .
( 40 ) The analysis of the available information showed that there is competition in the US @ American market for the affected goods with at least three manufacturers , around 30 suppliers , more than 15 importers and around 300 users .
According to the results of the investigation , as mentioned under recital 14 , the goods concerned and the Magnesia @ stones manufactured in the PRC or the USA and sold in the domestic markets were similar .
In addition , the study found that more than 50 % of the raw materials used by one of the US @ American manufacturers were imported from the People &apos;s Republic of China and that the manufacturing processes in the two countries did not differ significantly .
41 . This provisionally concludes that the United States of America was the most appropriate and acceptable comparative country within the meaning of Article 2 ( 7 ) of the Basic Regulation .
b ) Determination of normal value
42 . Pursuant to Article 2 ( 7 ) ( a ) of the Basic Regulation , the normal value for those exporting manufacturers to whom no MWB has been granted was determined on the basis of the manufacturer &apos;s verified information in the country of comparison .
Since the sales of the US @ American manufacturers were , according to the results of the investigation , trades in normal trade , the normal value for the types of goods comparable to the types of goods exported from the PRC to the Community was determined on the basis of the prices paid or paid on the US @ American domestic market .
( 43 ) The normal value was the weighted average domestic selling price charged by cooperating US @ American manufacturers to independent customers for product types with comparable MgO @ salary .
corrections may have been made for the different treatments of the different types of goods .
3.2 Determination of the normal value for the executing manufacturers to whom an MWB has been granted
( 44 ) It should be recalled that the dumping margin for companies granted an MWB was determined on the basis of their information on domestic sales and production costs for the goods concerned .
this data has been reviewed in the companies concerned .
( 45 ) In order to determine the normal value , the Commission first examined for each cooperating exporting manufacturer whether the total domestic sales of the goods concerned were representative compared to the total export sales to the Community .
In accordance with Article 2 ( 2 ) of the Basic Regulation , domestic sales were considered representative if the total quantity of these sales of each executing manufacturer corresponded to at least 5 % of the total volume of export sales of the manufacturer to the Community .
( 46 ) On this basis , it was established that the domestic sales of the goods concerned by an executive manufacturer were representative in the UZ .
the domestic sales of the goods concerned by the other executing manufacturer in the UZ were not representative .
( 47 ) For the exporting manufacturer with representative domestic sales , the Commission then identified the types of goods sold on the domestic market which were identical or directly comparable to the types sold for export to the Community .
48 . For any type sold on the domestic market which , according to the results of the investigation , was directly comparable to a type sold for export to the Community , it was examined whether domestic sales were sufficiently representative within the meaning of Article 2 ( 2 ) of the Basic Regulation .
the domestic sales of a certain type of goods were considered sufficiently representative if the total volume of domestic sales of this type in the UZ corresponded to 5 % or more of the total volume of export sales of the comparable type of goods to the Community .
( 49 ) This analysis showed that the executing manufacturer with overall representative sales did not sell all types of goods domestically in representative quantities .
( 50 ) Subsequently , the Commission examined whether the domestic sales of the individual types of goods sold in representative quantities on the domestic market could be regarded as transactions in normal trade , for which the share of profitable sales to independent customers was determined .
( 51 ) Domestic sales were considered profitable if the unit price of the respective product type corresponded at least to the production costs .
Therefore , the production costs for each type of goods sold in the UZ on the domestic market were determined .
( 52 ) As mentioned in recitals 50 and 51 , the share of profitable sales of the type of goods in question to independent customers on the domestic market was determined .
in cases where the sales quantity of a type sold at a net selling price in the amount of or above the calculated production costs corresponded to 80 % or more of the total sales quantity of that type and in which the weighted average price of the type in question corresponded at least to the production costs , the normal value was based on the actual domestic price determined as the weighted average of the prices of all domestic sales made in the UZ , regardless of whether these sales were profitable or not .
in cases where the volume of profitable sales of a type accounted for less than 80 % of the total sales volume of the type in question , or where the weighted average price of the type in question was below the production costs , the normal value was based on the actual domestic price , which was determined as a weighted average only of profitable sales , provided that the volume of these sales accounted for 10 % or more of the total sales volume of the type in question .
( 53 ) If the profitable sales amounted to less than 10 % of the total sales volume for one type , it was held that the sales volumes of this type were not sufficient to use the domestic price as an appropriate basis for determining the normal value .
( 54 ) The above analysis showed that certain types of goods were sold in normal trade .
( 55 ) For all types of goods which were either not sold in representative quantities or - due to the invoiced prices - not sold in normal trade ( see recitals 52 and 53 ) , the domestic prices of the executing manufacturer in question could not be used to determine the normal value , so that another method had to be used .
( 56 ) In cases where the domestic prices of a certain type sold by an executing manufacturer could not be used , the normal value had to be calculated on the basis of the costs of the manufacturer in question .
the normal value was calculated in accordance with Article 2 paragraph 3 of the Basic Regulation by adding a reasonable amount for the selling , administrative and overhead costs ( hereinafter referred to as &quot; VVG – @ costs &quot; ) and an appropriate profit margin to the production costs of the types carried out , if necessary .
To this end , the Commission examined whether the VVG ’ -@ costs and the profits made by the company domestically were reliable .
( 57 ) The actual VVG @ costs were considered reliable if the total volume of the company &amp; apos ; s domestic sales could be considered representative compared to the volume of export sales to the Community .
the domestic profit margin was determined by the domestic sales of the types sold in normal trade .
this was done using the method set out in recitals 45 , 48 , 52 and 53 .
for a company , the actual recorded VVG @ costs and profits could be used because it met the aforementioned criteria .
58 . For the other undertaking whose domestic sales were not representative , the normal value was determined in accordance with Article 2 ( 6 ) ( c ) of the Basic Regulation .
According to the results of the investigation , the cost structure of the other company with MWB and representative domestic sales for only a few types of goods showed such deviations that it did not provide a reasonable basis for determining the normal value .
However , according to the results of the investigation , the costs of the company whose domestic sales were not representative were reliable , so that the normal value was determined on the basis of the company &apos;s data corresponding to those of the other exporters / manufacturers of the same goods in that country of origin .
4 . Export prices
( 59 ) All export sales to the Community of exporters with MWB or IT were carried out either through related importers in the Community , related importers outside the Community or through companies that were not affiliated with the exporting manufacturers but worked closely with them or even had exclusive distribution rights .
in cases where exports were sold through affiliated companies , export prices were calculated in accordance with Article 2 ( 9 ) of the Basic Regulation .
in all cases where the exports of the goods concerned went to independent customers in the Community , the export price was calculated in accordance with Article 2 ( 8 ) of the basic regulation on the basis of the export prices actually paid or to be paid .
60 . Pursuant to Article 2 ( 9 ) of the Basic Regulation , corrections have been made for all costs incurred by the importer between import and resale , including VVG â – o@ costs and an appropriate profit margin .
In this case , the profit margin actually recorded by the cooperating independent introducers was regarded as a justifiable basis .
5 . Comparison
( 61 ) Normal value and export prices were compared at the level ex works and at the same trading level .
in the interest of a fair settlement , corrections were made on request in accordance with Article 2 ( 10 ) of the basic regulation for differences that demonstrably influenced prices and comparability of prices .
( 62 ) These corrections concerned differences in transport , insurance , provision , loading and ancillary costs , borrowing costs , commissions , import duties and customer service costs ( guarantee ) .
6 . Dumping span
6.1 Cooperating executive manufacturers to whom an MWB / IB has been granted
63 . In the case of the two undertakings to which an MWB has been granted , the weighted average normal value of the individual types of goods exported to the Community was compared with the weighted average export price of the corresponding type in accordance with Article 2 ( 11 ) of the Basic Regulation .
64 . In the case of the four undertakings to which an IB has been granted , the weighted average normal value of the individual types of the goods concerned exported to the Community for the country of comparison was compared with the weighted average export price of the corresponding type in accordance with Article 2 ( 11 ) of the Basic Regulation .
( 65 ) The provisional weighted average dumping margins , expressed as a percentage of cif @ prices free Community border , unpaid , reach the following values :
- Liaoning Mayerton Refractories Co . Ltd _ BAR _ 11,2 %
- Yingkou Sanhua Refractory Materials Co . Ltd _ BAR _ 34.1 %
- Yingkou Guangyang Refractories Co . Ltd _ BAR _ 55,7 %
- Yingkou Kyushu Refractories Co . Ltd _ BAR _ 55,7 %
- Dashiqiao Sanqiang Refractory Materials Co . Ltd _ BAR _ 99,9 %
- Yingkou Qinghua Refractories Co . Ltd _ BAR _ 41.4 % .
6.2 For all other executing manufacturers
( 66 ) In order to calculate the dumping margin for all other exporters in the People &apos;s Republic of China , the Commission first determined the scope of cooperation .
to this end , it compared the total imports of the goods concerned originating in the PRC based on the Eurostat @ statistics based on the method set out in recital 81 with the responses of the cooperating exporters in the PRC to the questionnaire .
after that , the cooperation was low .
( 67 ) In view of the low level of cooperation , the dumping range for all other exporters in the People &apos;s Republic of China was set at the highest dumping range determined for the cooperating exporting manufacturers , namely 99.9 % of the cif @ price free frontier of the Community , unpaid .
However , according to the results , the nationwide dumping range was higher than the residual damage range .
C. INCREASE
1 . Community production
( 68 ) In this investigation it was found that Magnesia @ stones were produced by :
- two applicant Community manufacturers and two other manufacturers who worked fully with the Commission during the investigation ( RHI , LWB , Refractarios Burceña S.L. and Ceramica del Nalon S.A. ) ;
- a manufacturer who answered the questionnaire in detail but spoke out against the procedure ( refratechnik ) ;
- seven other manufacturers and Assopiatrelle ( the Italian Fire Festival Association – @ Industry , which represents a production of 64,000 tonnes ) , which supported the Community industry but did not answer the questionnaire in detail .
another manufacturer sent a letter , but expressed neither agreement nor opposition .
2 . Definition of the Community industry
2.1 Manufacturers or manufacturers associated with the People &apos;s Republic of China who import the goods concerned from the People &apos;s Republic of China
( 69 ) The investigation showed that two of the cooperating manufacturers in the Community , namely RHI and Refratechnik , also imported the goods concerned from the People &apos;s Republic of China .
For this reason , it was examined whether these companies should be excluded from the Community sector in accordance with Article 4 ( 1 ) ( a ) of the basic regulation .
2.1.1 RHI
( 70 ) RHI produces in the community , but also introduces the affected goods from a related joint @ venture @ company in the People &apos;s Republic of China , RHI Liaoning .
it was found that in the UZ most of the Community sales of RHI were made in the community and only a small proportion came from the People &apos;s Republic of China .
this share is low , because the Chinese production of RHI is primarily intended for the rapidly growing Asian market .
RHI is also the largest manufacturer in the community , and its headquarters , R &amp; D @ center and largest production facilities are located in the community .
For this reason , it was found that RHI &apos;s core business with the goods concerned is located in the Community .
( 71 ) Subsequently , it was examined what effect the sale of the imported goods had on the total sales of the company in the Community .
the investigation showed that RHI had no significant profitability benefits from the resale of imports .
this resulted in a comparison of the profitability of the cooperating Community manufacturers .
( 72 ) Given the low proportion of imports and the fact that these imports did not have a significant positive impact on the profitability of Community sales as a whole , this undertaking was not immune from the negative effects of damaging dumping .
For this reason , it is considered that it would not be justified to exclude RHI from the Community sector .
2.1.2 Refratechnik
( 73 ) Refratechnik also produces the goods concerned in the Community and imports them from manufacturers in the People &apos;s Republic of China .
the investigation revealed that almost half of the company &apos;s joint sales in the People &apos;s Republic of China were manufactured in the UZ .
It was also noted that the expansion of business activity was largely made possible by an increase in imports from the People &apos;s Republic of China .
For this reason , it was held that the core business of Refratechnik is located not only in the community , but also in the People &apos;s Republic of China .
( 74 ) Subsequently , it was examined how the introduced sales affected the total sales of the Company in the Community .
the investigation revealed that refratechnik , unlike RHI , had a significant benefit from the resale of imports .
( 75 ) In view of the high proportion of imports in the total volume of sales in the Community and the fact that the core business appears to be gradually transferred to the People &apos;s Republic of China and refratechnik clearly benefited from the dumped imports , it was held that refratechnik should be excluded from the Community industry in accordance with Article 4 ( 1 ) ( a ) of the basic regulation and should be regarded as &quot; other market participants &quot; .
2.2 Community industry
76 . The production of the four Community manufacturers who worked fully on the investigation , including RHI and without refating technology , was 233732 tonnes during the period under investigation , representing 53 % of total Community production , thus forming the Community industry within the meaning of Articles 4 ( 1 ) and ( 5 ) ( 4 ) of the Basic Regulation .
( 77 ) The investigation revealed no self-consumption of the goods concerned for the Magnesia @ Stones producing industry .
some steel companies , on the other hand , produced Magnesia @ stones for their own consumption .
However , this amount was low compared to the production volumes of the refractory industry in the community .
Since this production is intended for self-consumption in the steel industry and none of the companies in the steel industry worked as manufacturers of magnesia @ stones ( although many of them received questionnaires ) , this part of the production does not seem to have any significant impact on the Community industry .
( 78 ) As the Community industry consisted of four undertakings and two of these undertakings accounted for around 2 % of the production volume , the following information for the Community industry was indexed for reasons of confidentiality .
3 . Community consumption
( 79 ) Consumption was determined on the basis of economic estimates transmitted by the Community industry according to customary practice .
The calculation of this data was based on steel production ( source : relevant reports from the International Iron and Steel Institute - IISI ) , divided by the average quantity of the goods concerned known to be required for the production of one tonne of steel .
( 80 ) The import quantities were determined on the basis of the Eurostat @ data for the relevant KN @ codes ( 68159100 , 68159910 , 68151010 , 68159990 , 69021000 and 69039020 ) .
of the determined quantities , deductions were made for those goods which , given their price , were clearly not the goods concerned .
the net volumes resulting after deduction ( for all countries combined 73291 tons and for the People &apos;s Republic of China 59831 tons ) were compared with the import volumes specified by the cooperating exporting manufacturers in the People &apos;s Republic of China ( about 42000 tons ) .
In view of the fact that some 13500 tonnes were imported from countries other than the People &apos;s Republic of China , ii according to the importers and users in the Community , the goods concerned were also imported by non-cooperating exporters in the People &apos;s Republic of China and iii received but did not cooperate with many other executive manufacturers in the People &apos;s Republic of China , the view was held that the Eurostat @ statistics correctly record the import quantities .
In addition , a Chinese press release ( China Metallurgical News , 4 January 2004 ) reported that 80,000 tonnes were exported to Europe in 2003 , suggesting that the aforementioned Eurostat @ figure is by no means too high for the UZ ( 59831 ) .
( 81 ) Sales of the Community industry on the Community market were determined on the basis of the verified responses from the five cooperating Community manufacturers ( including refresh technology ) to the questionnaire .
the remaining quantities ( i.e. consumption less imports less sales of the Community sector ) were regarded as sales of non-cooperating Community manufacturers .
( 82 ) Consumption determined in this way , the development of which is shown in the following table , shows that the demand for the goods concerned in the Community was practically constant during the reference period .
