( 93 ) Inventories increased by 8 % in the reference area .
the Community industry usually produces the goods concerned on order .
The level of inventories was therefore not found to be particularly meaningful for assessing the situation of the Community sector .
5.3 Sales , market shares , growth and average unit prices in the Community
( 94 ) The table below shows sales of the Community industry to independent customers in the Community .
Index 2001 = 100 _ BAR _ 2001 _ BAR _ 2002 _ BAR _ 2003 _ BAR _ UZ
Sales quantity ( in tonnes ) _ BAR _ 100 _ BAR _ 97 _ BAR _ 99 _ BAR _ 100 _ BAR _
Market share _ BAR _ 100 _ BAR _ 97 _ BAR _ 98 _ BAR _ 100 _ BAR _
Average selling price ( EUR / ton ) _ BAR _ 100 _ BAR _ 98 _ BAR _ 89 _ BAR _ 89 _ BAR _
( 95 ) The sales volumes and market share of the Community sector were constant during the reference period .
However , given the push for dumped imports into the Community market , this could only be achieved by reducing average selling prices by 11 % .
( 96 ) However , the 11 % decline in average prices does not reflect the decline in prices in key market segments sufficiently .
the goods concerned are mainly used in the steel industry for the lining of three types of vessels ( pans , converters and electric arc furnaces ) .
Initially , imports from the People &apos;s Republic of China consisted mainly of pans from the lower market segment .
in the reference period , however , there was a trend towards penetrating the higher segments of the converters and electric arc furnaces .
Converters and electric arc furnaces must achieve maximum useful life , which means that more expensive stones of high quality must be used to increase the number of furnace trips before renewal of the lining .
an analysis of the sales structure during the reference period showed that the Community industry was geared towards lower volumes for the high-quality market segments in order to defend itself against the pressure of imports from the People &apos;s Republic of China .
this development shows that the average prices of some types of goods fell by more than 11 % .
for example , the average price of the largest product group ( stones with 9 % residual carbon and melting magnesia ) fell by 19 % during the reference period .
( 97 ) In view of the increase in imports , the Community industry did not grow despite a reduction in its average prices .
rather , he was forced to reduce production capacity and jobs .
5.4 Profitability
( 98 ) The profitability shown in the table below was calculated as a return on sales in the Community market .
_ BAR _ 2001 _ BAR _ 2002 _ BAR _ 2003
Profitability of Community Sales _ BAR _ 100 _ BAR _ 76 _ BAR _ 26 _ BAR _ 45 _ BAR _
( 99 ) Profitability declined significantly between 2001 and 2003 as a result of price reductions , which coincided with the increase in dumped imports from the People &apos;s Republic of China .
in the UZ , profitability rose again slightly , primarily due to a cost reduction .
Although the Community industry made profits in the UZ , the profit margin was significantly lower than would normally be expected in the absence of dumped imports .
As the table shows , profitability was , as expected , much higher in 2001 , when the market share of dumped imports was still relatively low .
5.5 Return on investment ( RoI ) , cash flow , investments and capital raising opportunities
( 100 ) The table below provides an overview of the development of return on investment , cash flow and investments .
Index 2001 = 100 _ BAR _ 2001 _ BAR _ 2002 _ BAR _ 2003 _ BAR _ UZ
Return on investment ( RoI ) _ BAR _ 100 _ BAR _ 85 _ BAR _ 50 _ BAR _ 52 _ BAR _
Cash flow _ BAR _ 100 _ BAR _ 81 _ BAR _ 55 _ BAR _ 60 _ BAR
Investment _ BAR _ 100 _ BAR _ 75 _ BAR _ 131 _ BAR _ 134 _ BAR _
( 101 ) The table shows that the return on investment has largely developed in parallel with the return on sales ( see above ) .
Cash flow follows approximately the same trend , i.e. it declined from 2001 to 2003 and recovered slightly in the UZ .
the decline in return on investment and cash flow reflects the fact that average selling prices fell faster than the average cost of the goods sold .
( 102 ) The Community industry has increased its investment .
they were mainly used for the renewal of existing plants and machines , less for the construction of new production facilities .
( 103 ) However , the possibilities of the Community sector for raising capital from credit institutions or parent companies were not seriously affected during the reference period because companies belong to larger corporations .
capital raising opportunities are therefore primarily dependent on the strength of the Group and not necessarily on the circumstances in the business sector concerned .
this factor should therefore be irrelevant for this investigation .
5.6 Employment , productivity and wages
Index 2001 = 100 _ BAR _ 2001 _ BAR _ 2002 _ BAR _ 2003 _ BAR _ UZ
Number of employees _ BAR _ 100 _ BAR _ 91 _ BAR _ 92 _ BAR _ 93 _ BAR _
Productivity ( ton / workforce ) _ BAR _ 100 _ BAR _ 96 _ BAR _ 98 _ BAR _ 98 _ BAR _
Wages _ BAR _ 100 _ BAR _ 84 _ BAR _ 82 _ BAR _ 82 _ BAR _
( 104 ) As can be seen from the table , the Community industry reduced the number of its employees from 2001 to the UZ .
the increase between 2003 and the UZ can be explained by an increase in production .
Productivity was largely constant during the reference period .
( 105 ) Wages declined significantly in 2002 , but remained constant until the UZ .
The reason for this was a restructuring programme that year , as the development of production and employment shown above shows .
5.7 Amount of actual dumping margin
( 106 ) The dumping margins are listed in the section on dumping .
they are clearly above the threshold .
Moreover , the impact of the actual dumping range cannot be considered irrelevant given the volume and prices of dumped imports .
5.8 Effects of previous dumping or subsidy practices
( 107 ) The Community industry has not recovered from the effects of previous dumping or subsidy practices , as no relevant investigations have yet been carried out .
5.9 Conclusion on damage
( 108 ) While sales volumes and market share in the Community remained relatively constant , the Community industry was confronted with a 11 % decline in average prices during the reference period , although it changed its product -@ mix in favour of higher-value types of goods .
notwithstanding the cost savings , the profit margin decreased noticeably , so that the profits in the UZ were 55 % below the level of 2001 ; thus , the profit margin was significantly below the level that would have been expected without dumped imports .
( 109 ) The deterioration in the situation of the Community sector during the reference period is also reflected in the reduction in production and production capacity , the decline in wages , employment , return on investment and cash flow , and a lack of growth despite an 11 % reduction in average prices .
( 110 ) These negative developments fell at a time of relatively constant productivity , increasing investments and better capacity utilization .
the development of inventories and capital raising opportunities was not considered meaningful for the reasons set out above .
( 111 ) Taking into account all these indicators , the provisional conclusion is drawn that the Community industry in the UZ has been caused significant damage within the meaning of Article 3 of the basic regulation .
d . CITY URSAGE
1 . Preliminary note
( 112 ) It was also examined whether there was a causal link between the dumped imports from the PRC and the damage to the Community sector .
other known factors than dumped imports , which may have damaged the Community industry at the same time , were investigated to ensure that any damage caused by these other factors was not attributed to dumped imports .
2 . Effects of imports from the PRC
( 113 ) As has already been shown above , imports from the People &apos;s Republic of China rose by around 150 % and their market share by 118 % in the reference period .
as set out in recital 85 , imports from the People &apos;s Republic of China also fell by 22 % and a significant price undercut was noted ( cf . Recital 86 ) .
in response to imports , the Community industry maintained its sales volume ( not to jeopardise economies of scale ) , but had to significantly reduce its prices .
This price reduction led , among other things , to a 55 % decline in profitability .
thus , profitability is significantly lower than expected with this type of industry ; this level is no longer sustainable .
3 . Effects of imports from third countries
Index 2001 = 100 _ BAR _ 2001 _ BAR _ 2002 _ BAR _ 2003 _ BAR _ UZ
Imports from countries other than China _ BAR _ 100 _ BAR _ 90 _ BAR _ 140 _ BAR _ 141 _ BAR _
( 114 ) It is highly unlikely that imports originating in third countries such as the Republic of Korea and Brazil may have contributed to damaging the Community sector .
the market share of imports from countries other than the People &apos;s Republic of China was only around 3 % in the UZ .
Moreover , the average prices of imports from the Republic of Korea and Brazil ( i.e. third countries alongside the People &apos;s Republic of China , from which the largest quantities were imported ) were 25 % or 47 % higher than the prices of imports originating in the People &apos;s Republic of China .
Given the market share and the relatively high prices of imports from other third countries , it can be concluded that these imports can , if at all , have made only a minimal contribution to damaging the Community economy .
4 . Effects of competition between Community manufacturers and overcapacity
( 115 ) Some interested parties claimed that the Community industry had been forced to reduce its prices in competition to a damaging level due to overcapacity of the refractory industry .
However , the capacity utilization determined in the study for the reference period , the development of which is listed in indexed form under recital 90 , does not confirm this claim .
rather , it was comparable to the capacity utilization of the steel industry and other similar industries .
Although capacity was clearly reduced and prices fell , this was primarily a response to the increase in dumped imports from the People &apos;s Republic of China .
the Commission also points out that a comprehensive restructuring of the Community &amp; apos ; s refractory industry took place as early as the late 1990s .
5 . Effects of developments in the steel industry
( 116 ) It was claimed that technical progress , which enabled the production of stones with a longer service life and efficient steel production , had caused damage to the Community sector .
During the investigation , several steel producers stated that their consumption of magnesia @ stones per tonne of steel produced had fallen as a result of technical progress .
_ BAR _ 2001 _ BAR _ 2002 _ BAR _ 2003
