Consumption of Magnesia @ stones EU @ 25 ( in tonnes ) _ BAR _ 399563 _ BAR _ 397203 _ BAR _ 401499 _ BAR _ 400638 _ BAR _
Stone consumption in the steel industry ( tonnes per kiloton ) _ BAR _ 2,21 _ BAR _ 2,20 _ BAR _ 2,19 _ BAR _ 2,16 _ BAR _
this table shows that Magnesia @ stones account for only about 2 % of steel production .
a decline in this share would therefore not explain the decline in selling prices and profitability described in the section on damage .
For this reason , it is considered that the higher technical quality of the stones could not have been a major cause of damage to the Community sector .
( 117 ) The investigation revealed that some steel producers still produce a certain proportion of Magnesia @ stones themselves .
However , there are no signs that this practice would have been extended over time .
Moreover , since no steel company worked on the investigation as a manufacturer of Magnesia @ stones , it can be assumed that this production sector had no effect on the economic situation of the Community sector .
6 . Effects of exchange rate fluctuations
( 118 ) Another factor allegedly responsible for the damage was the change in the exchange rate of the dollar and the euro .
This could be relevant , as the Chinese renminbi has been pegged to the dollar for many years ; allegedly , the fluctuations in the exchange rate of the dollar and the euro have made exports to the community more attractive to Chinese manufacturers .
( 119 ) However , the dollar ’ s price loss against the euro did not always coincide with the rise in imports .
the decline in the dollar price began in June 2002 , while imports rose significantly as early as 2001 .
Moreover , the freight costs from the People &apos;s Republic of China to the Community increased considerably in the reference period .
If imports from the People &apos;s Republic of China had increased only because the exchange rate change had improved , a decline or at least a stabilisation of imports would have been expected as soon as the increased freight costs compensated for the exchange rate change .
although such compensation actually occurred ( freight costs increased by around 25 % in the last 15 months of the reference period according to P &amp; O Nedlloyd ) , imports continued to increase .
( 120 ) For this reason , it is provisionally concluded that the impact of the exchange rate changes can hardly have contributed to damaging the Community sector .
7 . Effects of Community imports into the Community
( 121 ) Some interested parties claimed that the damage was self-caused because the Community industry introduced the goods concerned from the People &apos;s Republic of China .
As stated above , imports from the PRC accounted for 5 % of its total Community market sales in the case of RHI , which is part of the Community industry .
the share and difference in the prices of these imports compared to Community sales are relatively small and may not have had a major impact on the market .
8 . Effects of Community exports
( 122 ) In the UZ , the Community industry accounted for around 27 % of its Community production .
export volumes decreased only marginally during this period .
However , the profitability of these exports was higher than that of Community sales , so it cannot be claimed that they have helped to damage the Community sector .
9 . Conclusion on the cause of damage
( 123 ) As already stated , the damage in this case was primarily in the form of price pressure , which caused a decline in profitability .
Taking into account the fact that the prices of rapidly increasing imports from the PRC were well below those of the Community sector , there is nothing to suggest that the factors mentioned above may have been a major cause of significant damage to the Community sector .
no other factors were found during the investigation that could have caused the significant damage .
( 124 ) On the basis of this analysis of the impact of all known factors on the situation of the Community sector , it is provisionally concluded that there is a causal link between the dumped imports from the People &apos;s Republic of China and the significant damage to the Community sector .
E. COMMUNITY INTERESTS
1 . General considerations
( 125 ) It was examined whether there were compelling reasons for the conclusion that the introduction of anti-dumping duties on imports from the country concerned would run counter to the Community interest .
the Commission sent questionnaires to importers , industrial users and suppliers .
Answers were received by one of 14 users , five suppliers and three independent introducers .
( 126 ) On the basis of the information received by the cooperating parties , the following conclusions were drawn .
2 . Interest of the Community industry
( 127 ) It is well known that the Community industry includes four manufacturers employing around 800 people in the production and sale of the goods concerned .
it should also be recalled that the economic indicators for the Community sector examined above showed a deterioration in business results during the reference period .
Despite the slight improvement in the UZ , the Community industry was unable to achieve a satisfactory financial situation due to dumped imports from the People &apos;s Republic of China .
( 128 ) It is clear that , in the event of a waiver of measures , more and more production facilities in the Community will be closed and that steel companies will be much more dependent on Chinese goods .
there are currently only a few production sites worldwide , and the majority of raw materials ( especially magnesium oxide ) are located in the People &apos;s Republic of China .
For this reason , there are no major sources of supply in other third countries .
As a result , the introduction of anti-dumping measures would be obviously beneficial to the Community industry .
( 129 ) For these reasons , it is provisionally concluded that the introduction of anti-dumping measures would be in the interests of the Community sector .
3 . Interest of independent importers
( 130 ) Four companies answered the questionnaire for independent importers , although only two of them imported the goods concerned into the UZ .
the cooperating importers opposed the introduction of measures and claimed that there were only a few major manufacturers of refractory products in the Community and that imports from the People &apos;s Republic of China stimulated competition on the Community market .
should measures be introduced and prices rise , Chinese companies may reduce their Community sales and importers would incur losses from reduced trade and profitability .
( 131 ) An importer argued that he might have to close his business with eight employees , since the goods concerned had a significant share of his business activities .
However , the aim of the anti-dumping measures is neither to prevent the import of the goods concerned nor to make the activities of importers in the Community more difficult .
Since the proposed measures concern only a relatively small part of the total cost of the Community steel industry and there are business relations between Chinese exporting manufacturers and Community users based on specific technical requirements , it is likely that the traditional business of importers will continue even if anti-dumping measures are introduced against dumped imports .
( 132 ) It was also noted that the introduction of measures would not have any significant consequences for the other importer , since the goods concerned have only a share of less than 1 % of the company &apos;s turnover .
4 . Interest of suppliers
( 133 ) The suppliers involved in the investigation supported the procedure .
two companies that supplied the community &apos;s industry with the most important raw material for Magnesia @ stones ( stillburnt magnesite ) claimed that they should have stopped supplying the refractory @ industry a few years ago , as first raw materials from the People &apos;s Republic of China and later also Magnesia @ stones from the People &apos;s Republic of China came onto the market .
5 . Interest of users
5.1 Prelude
( 134 ) 14 user companies , i.e. steel producers , answered the questionnaire and another manufacturer and the Steel Economic Association submitted opinions .
another user supported the Community industry &amp; apos ; s request , but all other steel companies opposed the introduction of anti-dumping measures .
Overall , user companies accounted for around 38 % of the joint consumption of Magnesia @ Steinen .
5.2 highly sensitive goods
( 135 ) Fireproof materials are of utmost strategic importance for the steel industry .
the entire steel passes through converters , ovens and pans walled out with Magnesia @ stones .
Supply difficulties could therefore have significant consequences in the form of production interruptions , repairs or safety problems .
for this reason , stones of high quality , i.e. long service life , and good technical support for this type of goods are very important .
due to the high technical requirements , a lot of time , high investments and research are required to establish a supplier relationship .
switching from a Chinese manufacturer to another manufacturer would also be very difficult .
steel producers claimed that they had made good progress with Chinese manufacturers and their Community importers over the last two years , mainly through improvements in efficiency and innovation .
( 136 ) Companies objecting to the introduction of measures therefore fear that there may be bottlenecks in the supply of high-quality stones and adequate technical assistance .
they fear that Chinese manufacturers would withdraw from the Community market if measures were introduced .
in addition , the largest deposits of magnesite , the most important raw material for Magnesia @ stones , are located in the People &apos;s Republic of China .
the steel industry is therefore afraid that its relations with Chinese raw material suppliers could deteriorate .
( 137 ) However , as stated above , the anti-dumping measures do not aim to prevent the import of the goods concerned or to make the activity of steel producers more difficult .
this means that non-harmful imports could be further imported into the Community .
Consequently , existing relations with Chinese exporters could be maintained even if anti-dumping measures were introduced against dumped imports .
This is also due to the fact that the goods concerned have only such an insignificant share of the total production costs of steel producers that measures would have only minor effects on the costs of users ( see recital 142 ) .
( 138 ) It should also be borne in mind that the goods concerned are of strategic importance to the steel industry .
in the event of a waiver of measures , there is a risk that the entire production of the goods concerned will be transferred to the People &apos;s Republic of China in the long term .
Given that there are no major manufacturers in other third countries , such dependence on Chinese imports is clearly not a viable scenario for the steel industry
( 139 ) Furthermore , there is no evidence that access to raw materials could be made more difficult for steel producers who produce Magnesia @ stones for their own use .
5.3 Market structure
( 140 ) The user industry claimed that the measures would strengthen a market structure with a few major manufacturers .
the users argued that this lack of competition was the result of mergers and acquisitions in the refractory industry in the 1990s .
( 141 ) The largest manufacturer in the Community had a market share of around 30 % in the UZ , which is unlikely to be sufficient to control and dominate the market .
this is underpinned by the fact that this market share declined as a result of imports from the People &apos;s Republic of China .
as stated above , these imports will in all likelihood continue even after the introduction of measures .
moreover , many small businesses in the community and even some steel companies themselves produce Magnesia @ stones , and during the investigation no evidence was presented that the major manufacturers in the community dominated the market in the alleged way .
since no evidence of anti-competitive behaviour has been presented , the claim remains unfounded and unproven .
5.4 Higher costs
( 142 ) The steel industry also argued that anti-dumping duties on Magnesia @ stones would incur additional costs on the highly price-sensitive steel market and especially in competition with steel producers from third countries .
For this reason , anti-dumping duties would affect the competitiveness of the steel industry , especially since the pressure on the markets for other raw materials for steel products is also very strong .
( 143 ) Nevertheless , the answers of the user industry to the questionnaire show that the Magnesia @ stones account for well below 1 % of the total cost .
Consequently , the proposed anti-dumping duties would only have a marginal impact on the total cost of steel production .
the latest developments in the steel industry clearly show a recovery in selling prices and profitability , further reducing the share of Magnesia @ stones in total sales .
5.5 Conclusion on the interest of users
( 144 ) In view of the foregoing , it is unlikely that the anti-dumping measures on the Community market would conceal supply or affect competition , especially as the Chinese Magnesia @ stones are likely to continue to hold their market share .
the increase in costs would only be marginal and would not significantly affect the competitiveness of the steel industry .
for these reasons , it is provisionally held that the interests of users do not speak against the introduction of measures .
6 . Conclusion on the Community interest
( 145 ) The introduction of measures against imports of Magnesia @ stones originating in the country concerned would clearly be in the interests of the Community sector .
as far as importers / traders and user industries are concerned , any impact on the prices of the Magnesia @ stones should be minor .
By contrast , the market share and profitability losses of the Community sector and the decline in its prices are clearly larger .
( 146 ) In view of the foregoing , it is provisionally concluded that there are no compelling reasons against the introduction of anti-dumping duties on imports of Magnesia @ stones originating in the People &apos;s Republic of China .
F. ANTIDUMPINGMASSNAHMEN
1 . Damage reduction threshold
( 147 ) In view of the conclusions on dumping , damage and Community interest , measures should be introduced to prevent further damage to the Community sector by dumped imports .
( 148 ) Customs duties shall be set at a level sufficient to eliminate the damage caused by these imports without exceeding the identified dumping margin .
in determining the rate of duty required to eliminate the effects of damaging dumping , it was assumed that any measures should enable the Community industry to cover its production costs and achieve an overall adequate pre-tax profit , which could be achieved by a sector of this kind in the sector under normal conditions of competition , i.e. without dumped imports , when selling similar goods in the Community .
This calculation was based on profit margins before dumped imports based on a profit margin before tax of 8 % of sales .
on this basis , a non-damaging price of the similar commodity was determined for the Community industry .
the non-damaging price was determined on the basis of production costs plus the aforementioned profit margin of 8 % .
( 149 ) The necessary price increase was then determined by comparing the weighted average import price with the non-damaging price .
Import prices have been revised upwards by 10 % for three reasons .
Firstly , the production facilities of the Community sector were near the steel mills , while the cost of transporting from the port of import and the cost of insurance for imports was usually higher .
Secondly , the price charged by the Community industry to the respective steel mills during the sale also included technical support , which was usually not the case with the exporters .
Thirdly , all sales of the Community industry were at the level of end consumers , while many import business was at the level of traders who had additional costs .
( 150 ) Any differences resulting from the comparison were expressed as a percentage of the average cif @ import value .
the comparison was based on the groups of goods formed according to PCN -@ numbers ( see recital 11 ) .
( 151 ) The provisional weighted claims margins for companies granted either individual treatment or market economy status were :
- Liaoning Mayerton Refractories Co . Ltd _ BAR _ 17.1 %
- Yingkou Sanhua Refractory Materials Co . Ltd _ BAR _ 42,1 %
- Yingkou Kyushu Refractories Co . Ltd _ BAR _ 21.9 %
- Yingkou Guangyang Refractories Co . Ltd _ BAR _ 21.9 % _ BAR
- Yingkou Qinghua Refractories Co . Ltd _ BAR _ 54.6 %
- Dashiqiao Sanqiang Refractory Materials Co . Ltd _ BAR _ 66.1 % .
( 152 ) In connection with the calculation of the nationwide damage reduction threshold for all other exporters in the People &apos;s Republic of China , it must be taken into account that cooperation was low .
For this reason , a range was calculated based on the data of those cooperating exporters who were not granted MWB or IB .
since this damage compensation threshold was lower than the highest damage margin in the case of the companies listed above , and in order not to reward non-cooperation , the nationwide damage margin was set at the level of the highest range determined above , i.e. 66.1 % .
2 . Provisional measures
( 153 ) On the basis of the foregoing , it was held that , in accordance with Article 7 ( 2 ) of the Basic Regulation , provisional anti-dumping duties on imports of the goods concerned originating in the People &apos;s Republic of China should be introduced .
in accordance with the rule of the lower tariff , anti-dumping duties should be set at the level of the dumping or damage margin , depending on which of the two is lower .
Since cooperation was low , the residual range should be set in the amount of the highest for cooperating exporting manufacturers , i.e. in the amount of 66.1 % of the cif @ price free frontier of the Community , unpaid .
the company-specific anti-dumping duties set out in this Regulation were set on the basis of the findings of this investigation .
they thus reflect the situation of the companies during this investigation .
In contrast to the nationwide tariffs on &quot; all other companies &quot; , these tariffs therefore apply exclusively to imports of goods originating in the country concerned and manufactured by the named legal entities .
imported goods which manufacture other companies not having their name and address in the part of this decision , including those affiliated with the companies expressly mentioned , are not subject to these individual duties , but to the customs duty applicable to &quot; all other companies &quot; .
