Council Regulation ( EC ) No 564 / 2005
of 8 April 2005
amending Regulation No 1601 / 2001 establishing a final anti-dumping duty and finally collecting the provisional anti-dumping duty on imports of certain iron or steel cables and ropes originating in the Czech Republic , Russia , Thailand and Turkey
the COUNCIL OF THE EUROPEAN UNION
Having regard to the Treaty establishing the European Community ,
Having regard to Council Regulation ( EC ) No 384 / 96 of 22 December 1995 on the protection against dumped imports from non-European Community countries &#91; 1 &#93; ( hereinafter referred to as the &quot; Basic Regulation &quot; ) , and in particular Article 11 ( 3 ) thereof ,
on a proposal from the Commission after consultations in the Advisory Committee ,
Considering the following reasons :
A. PREPARATION PROCEDURE
( 1 ) On 5 May 2000 , the Commission opened an anti-dumping procedure &#91; 2 &#93; concerning imports of certain iron or steel cables and ropes originating in Turkey , among others .
( 2 ) This procedure ultimately led to the introduction of a final anti-dumping duty under Council Regulation ( EC ) No 1601 / 2001 &#91; 3 &#93; in order to eliminate the harmful effects of dumping .
ANTRAG ON INTRODUCTION OF A INTERIMUM TRANSPORT
( 3 ) Has Çelik ve Halat Sanayi Ticaret A.S. ( hereinafter referred to as &quot; Has Çelik &quot; or &quot; Applicant &quot; ) , a Turkish executive manufacturer of certain cables and ropes made of iron or steel subject to current anti-dumping measures , submitted an application for a partial interim review of Regulation ( EC ) No 1601 / 2001 .
4 . This request , in accordance with Article 11 ( 3 ) of the Basic Regulation , argued that the circumstances relating to dumping on the basis of which the measures in force were introduced had changed and that these changes were permanent .
( 5 ) According to the application , the applicant made structural changes that had a significant impact on the normal value .
In addition , the applicant argued that a comparison of the normal value based on his costs or domestic prices with export prices to the Community would result in a dumping range that would be significantly below the 17.8 % anti-dumping duty applicable to imports produced by him .
therefore , maintaining the current level of measures based on the previously determined dumping range is no longer necessary to compensate for dumping .
6 . Following consultations in the Consultative Committee , the Commission concluded that there was sufficient evidence to justify the opening of a partial interim review , so that it published a notice &#91; 4 &#93; and began an investigation which was limited to determining the existence of dumping with the applicant .
C. PROCEDURE
( 7 ) The Commission officially informed the exporting country representatives and the applicant of the initiation of the partial interim review and gave all parties directly concerned the opportunity to present their position in writing and request a hearing .
the Liaison Committee of the European Foundation of the Wire Rope Industries ( EWRIS ) submitted an opinion .
( 8 ) The Commission also sent the applicant a questionnaire which he answered within the time limit set in the notice .
( 9 ) The Commission obtained all the information deemed necessary for dumping , examined it and carried out a inspection visit to the applicant &amp; apos ; s operation .
( 10 ) The dumping investigation concerned the period from 1 July 2003 to 29 February 2004 ( hereinafter referred to as &quot; examination period &quot; ) .
WARE
affected goods
similar goods
( 12 ) Like the previous investigation , the review also showed that the SWR produced and sold or exported to the Community by the applicant in Turkey has the same basic material characteristics and uses , so that they are to be regarded as similar goods within the meaning of Article 1 ( 4 ) of the basic regulation .
E. DUMPING
Normal value
( 13 ) In determining the normal value , it was first examined whether the domestic sales of the similar goods made by the applicant were representative compared to its export sales to the Community .
this was the case because the quantities sold domestically complied with at least 5 % of its total export sales to the Community in accordance with Article 2 ( 2 ) of the Basic Regulation .
( 14 ) Subsequently , for each of the types sold by the applicant on the domestic market which , according to the results of the investigation , were directly comparable to the types exported to the Community , it was examined whether the domestic sales were sufficiently representative within the meaning of Article 2 ( 2 ) of the basic regulation .
this was considered to be the case if the total amount of domestic sales of a type during the period under investigation was at least 5 % of the total amount of export sales of the same type to the Community .
for most of the types exported to the Community during the period under investigation , a comparable type sold in representative quantities on the domestic market could be determined .
( 15 ) For the types of goods that reached the 5 % threshold , it was then examined in each case whether domestic sales could be regarded as transactions in normal trade by determining the share of profitable sales to independent customers .
in all cases , more than 80 % of the total domestic sales of the respective type were profitable , so that the normal value was based on the weighted average of all domestic sales during the period under investigation .
( 16 ) For the types exported to the Community for which , according to the results of the investigation , no comparable types were sold on the domestic market , the normal value referred to in Article 2 ( 3 ) and ( 6 ) of the Basic Regulation was calculated on the basis of the applicant &apos;s manufacturing costs for the types carried out in question plus an appropriate amount for selling , administrative and overheads ( hereinafter referred to as &quot; VVG @ Costs &quot; ) and for profits .
the VVG @ costs were based on those recorded by the applicant in domestic sales of the similar goods .
the profit margin was based on that which the applicant achieved in domestic sales of similar goods in normal trade .
Export price
( 17 ) Since all exports of the goods concerned were sold directly to independent customers in the Community , the export price was determined in accordance with Article 2 ( 8 ) of the basic regulation on the basis of the prices actually paid or to be paid .
Comparison
( 18 ) The comparison of the normal value with the export price took place at the level ex works and at the same trading level .
in the interest of a fair settlement , corrections were made on request in accordance with Article 2 ( 10 ) of the Basic Regulation for demonstrably price and comparability influencing differences in transport costs , insurance costs , provision , loading and ancillary costs , borrowing costs and commissions .
Dumping range
( 19 ) In accordance with Article 2 ( 11 ) of the Basic Regulation , the weighted average corrected normal value was compared with the weighted average net export price ex works of the comparable product type in order to determine the dumping range for each product type .
( 20 ) This comparison showed that there was no dumping .
F. DAUERHAFTE CHANGE OF ENVIRONMENT
21 . Pursuant to Article 11 ( 3 ) of the Basic Regulation , it was also examined whether it could reasonably be assumed that circumstances had changed permanently .
( 22 ) In this respect , the investigation showed that the applicant made structural changes with a significant impact on production and organization , which resulted in significantly higher production efficiency and thus a decrease in production costs , so that the normal value was lower compared to that in the period under investigation of the previous study ( 1 April 1999 to 31 March 2000 ) .
export prices rose over the same period , and the investigation showed no evidence that this increase was temporary .
( 23 ) It is therefore concluded that circumstances have changed permanently , in particular the rise in exports to the Community and the simultaneous decline in production costs .
g . ANTIDUMPINGMASSE
( 24 ) Since no dumping has been established , the measures vis-à-vis the applicant should be repealed .
( 25 ) Interested parties were informed of the facts and considerations on the basis of which an amendment to Regulation ( EC ) No 1601 / 2001 should be recommended and were given the opportunity to comment .
( 26 ) As a result , the EMRIS made some general comments , which mainly concerned rising commodity prices after the period under investigation .
the EMRIS did not question the above dumping findings , but expressed concern that the applicant might be able to practice dumping again .
( 27 ) With regard to raw material prices , it should be noted that although they may have risen after the period under investigation , this could not be taken into account in the dumping investigation for the applicant .
in the present case , the most important raw material is wire rod , a simple steel product whose prices usually fluctuate rapidly .
Therefore , an increase in the prices of such a raw material cannot be regarded as a permanent change that could invalidate the above findings .
( 28 ) Finally , it should be noted that the measures will only be repealed for the applicant and not for Turkey as a whole , so that , in accordance with Article 11 ( 6 ) of the basic regulation , the applicant will continue to be involved in the procedure and can be re-examined in the context of a subsequent review carried out for Turkey -
has FOLLOWING REGULATION :
Article 1
Regulation ( EC ) No 1601 / 2004 is amended as follows :
in the table in Article 1 paragraph 3 the duty rate ( % ) for the company Has Çelik ve Halat Sanayi Ticaret A.S.
( TARIC – @ additional code A220 )
&quot; 0 . &quot;
Article 2
this Regulation shall enter into force on the day following its publication in the Official Journal of the European Union .
this Regulation is binding in all its parts and applies directly in each Member State .
